<subsection xml:id="subsec-dividing-lines-proportionally">
            <title>Dividing lines proportionally</title>
            <p>
                A line can be divided into a given number of equal parts/proportions.
            </p>
            <activity>
                <p>
                    Here is an activity on how to divide a line proportionally into 5 equal parts.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Draw a line <m>AB</m> and <m>AC</m> as shown below   
                </p>

                <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Proportional division of lines</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="lines">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[thick,black] (-2,0) node[left] {$A$} -- (3,0) node[right]{$B$};
                        \draw[thick,black] (-2,0) -- (4,4) node[right]{$C$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>

                <p>
                    Using a pair of compasses, draw 5 arcs of equal lengths on line <m>AC.</m>
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Proportional division of lines</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="proportional-lines">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[thick,black] (0,0) node[left] {$A$} -- (5,0) node[right]{$B$};
                        \draw[thick,black] (0,0) -- (6,6) node[right]{$C$};
                        \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5}{
                          \draw(\x,\x+0.25)--(\x,\x-0.25) node[right]{$\x$};
                        };
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>

                <p>
                    Using a set square and a ruler, draw parallel lines from arcs marked on line <m>AC</m> to line <m>AB.</m>
                </p>

                <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription>Proportional division of lines-2</shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="proportional-lines-2">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[thick,black] (0,0) node[left] {$A$} -- (5,0) node[right]{$B$};
                        \draw[thick,black] (0,0) -- (6,6) node[right]{$C$};
                        \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5}{
                          \draw(\x,\x+0.25)--(\x,\x-0.25) node[right]{$\x$};
                        };

                        \draw[thick,blue] (1,1) -- (1,0) node[below]{$P$};
                        \draw[thick,blue] (2,2) -- (2,0) node[below]{$Q$};
                        \draw[thick,blue] (3,3) -- (3,0) node[below]{$R$};
                        \draw[thick,blue] (4,4) -- (4,0) node[below]{$S$};
                        \draw[thick,blue] (5,5) -- (5,0);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>

                <p>
                    Measure the distance between lines: <m>AP, PQ, QR, RS, SB.</m> Cpompare and discuss your findings with other learners.
                </p>
            </activity>
                
    </subsection>